vate key.</p>\n            <p>A public key is used for encryption, while a private key is used for decryption.</p>\n            <h2>How does it work?</h2>\n            <p>Here's a simplified example of how asymmetric cryptography works:</p>\n            <p>1. Generate a pair of keys: a public key and a private key.</p>\n            <p>2. Use the public key to encrypt the data.</p>\n            <p>3. Use the private key to decrypt the data.</p>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"section\">\n            <h2>Visualizing Asymmetric Cryptography</h2>\n            <p>A simple example of an asymmetric encryption algorithm using RSA (Rivest-Shamir-Adleman) is used here.</p>\n            <p><img src=\"asymmetric-encryption-example.jpg\" alt=\"Asymmetric Encryption Example\"></p>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"section\">\n            <h2>Real-world Applications</h2>\n            <p>Asymmetric cryptography has numerous real-world applications, including secure online transactions and communication.</p>\n            <p><img src=\"real-world-applications.jpg\" alt=\"Real-world Applications\"></p>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"footer\">\n            <p>&copy; 2023 Asymmetric Cryptography Example</p>\n            <a href=\"#\" class=\"footer a\">Learn More</a>\n            <a href=\"#\" class=\"footer a\">Contact Us</a>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n    <script>\n        // Limited interactivity\n        const encryptionButton = document.getElementById('encryption-button');\n        const decryptionButton = document.getElementById('decryption-button');\n        const visualizationButton = document.getElementById('visualization-button');\n\n        encryptionButton.addEventListener('click', () => {\n            // Simulate encryption\n            const encryptedData = 'This is some encrypted data';\n            const encryptedDataBlob = new Blob([encryptedData], { type: 'text/plain' });\n            const link = document.createElement('a');\n            link.href =